## Before You Start — Canvas Planning

The most impactful decisions happen before the first brushstroke. Resolution problems, bad crops, and color mismatches are almost always caused by choices made at canvas creation — not at export.

**Rule 1 — Start big.** It is always possible to scale down. It is never possible to scale up without quality loss. If there is any chance the artwork will appear on a desk mat (largest OIS product), the canvas must accommodate it from the start.

**Rule 2 — Compose for crops.** A single OIS painting may appear on a 31.5-inch wide desk mat, a 10×10 square print, a 4-inch coaster, and a YouTube banner — all at different aspect ratios. Keep the focal point in the center third of the composition. Leave enough secondary elements and negative space around the subject that landscape, portrait, and square crops all retain compositional integrity.

**Rule 3 — Overlay your crop targets on the sketch.** Before committing to the final painting, draw rectangles representing each target product format on top of the sketch. Verify that the key subject survives every anticipated crop. This takes five minutes and prevents weeks of rework.

**Rule 4 — Work in RGB.** Paint in RGB with CMYK soft-proofing enabled (Photoshop: View → Proof Colors). Convert to CMYK only at the final export stage. This preserves the widest color gamut during the creative process. See [Color — RGB vs CMYK](#color--rgb-vs-cmyk).

**Rule 5 — Set display brightness to 50–60%.** Especially on iPad/Procreate. Backlit screens are significantly brighter than printed output. Painting at full brightness virtually guarantees disappointment with print results.

---

## The Master Canvas Strategy

Create one master file large enough to cover every product. From it, derive all product-specific exports.

**Recommended master canvas:**

- **Minimum:** 13,500px on the long edge at 300 PPI
- **Ideal:** 15,000 × 9,000px at 300 PPI (landscape)
- **Format:** PSD or TIFF, layered, RGB
- **Color profile:** sRGB IEC61966-2.1 or Display P3

This single canvas covers every current OIS Fourthwall product at 300 DPI except the 24×36 poster (which needs 7,200 × 10,800px and should be treated as a separate deliverable if required).

**Three derived assets from one master:**

- **Landscape:** ~15,000 × 9,000px (desk mats, banners, gaming pads)
- **Square:** ~9,000 × 9,000px (10×10 prints, coasters, profile pics)
- **Portrait:** ~7,200 × 10,800px (18×24 posters — requires planning or separate composition)

The landscape-to-portrait crop is the hardest problem. Four approaches in order of preference:

1. **Pre-planned composition** — design with generous space so both orientations retain the subject
2. **Product-specific variations** — create distinct compositions for landscape vs portrait formats
3. **Pattern/mirror techniques** — duplicate and mirror motifs for extreme aspect ratios (desk mats)
4. **Content-Aware extension** — Photoshop can stretch simple backgrounds, but only works with uniform areas

---

## Color — RGB vs CMYK

**The rule: Work in RGB. Export to CMYK.**

RGB files are smaller (3 channels vs 4), preserve a wider color gamut during editing, and can be reused for screen output without color loss. This is the modern professional standard for print-on-demand workflows.

**Practical workflow (Photoshop):**

1. Paint in RGB with View → Proof Colors (Cmd+Y) set to Working CMYK
2. Use View → Gamut Warning to flag out-of-gamut colors
3. Deep blues, saturated reds, and bright oranges are the most common offenders
4. When ready to export: save the RGB master first
5. Duplicate the file, convert via Edit → Convert to Profile (not Image → Mode)
6. Save the CMYK version as a separate deliverable

**Exception — Fine art giclée prints (posters):** Stay in sRGB even for the final print file. Modern inkjet printers use 8–12 ink tanks that reproduce a broader gamut than CMYK. Fourthwall's poster products use digital inkjet printing, making RGB the better color space for these.

**For Procreate users:** Set canvas to actual print dimensions at 300 PPI. Choose sRGB for maximum compatibility. Set iPad brightness to 50–60% while painting to simulate print luminance.

**For sublimation products (desk mats, mouse pads, coasters):** Colors will print darker and less saturated than screen previews. Deliberately push brightness and saturation 10–15% beyond your target appearance during the painting process.

