## Print Methods & What They Mean for Art

Understanding the print method tells the artist what to expect and what to avoid.

### Sublimation (Desk Mats, Mouse Pads, Coasters)

Embeds dye into the material using heat transfer. Edge-to-edge coverage. Vibrant on white/light substrates. Gradients work well — most forgiving method for painterly artwork. **Colors print darker and less saturated than screen.** Compensate by pushing brightness and saturation 10–15%.

### Digital Inkjet / Giclée (Posters, Art Prints)

Water-based inkjet at 300 DPI. Most color-accurate method. Handles gradients, subtle tonal shifts, and fine detail well. Stay in sRGB for these — modern inkjet printers reproduce a wider gamut than CMYK.

### DTG — Direct to Garment (T-shirts, Lightweight Apparel)

Sprays ink into fabric fibers. Soft, breathable prints. Works well on light fabrics. On dark garments, a white underbase prints first — whites may appear slightly faded. Red ink is problematic on dark fabrics (switch to DTFx for reds on dark). Minimum 200 DPI. Minimum 5,000 × 5,000px upload. PNG with transparent background required.

### DTFx — Direct to Film Express (Hoodies, Heavyweight Apparel)

Prints onto a 0.1mm film bonded to fabric. Brighter, more vibrant than DTG — close to screen printing quality. Film is not breathable, so best on midweight and heavyweight garments. Transparent background PNG required. Avoid large solid fills on lightweight tees. Break up designs with negative space. Minimum text size: 1mm / 4pt.

### Screen Printing (MOQ Products Only)

Highest garment quality — same technique as major retailers. Requires minimum order quantities. PNG only, 300 DPI minimum. Avoid gradients entirely. Use solid, well-defined shapes.

### Embroidery

Stitches artwork into fabric. Maximum 5–6 thread colors from a 15-color palette. Minimum line thickness: 0.05″ (4pt). Minimum uppercase text height: 0.3″. Standard area: 15,000 stitches across 4″ × 4″. Gradients, photorealistic images, and fine detail are incompatible.

