## OBS Stream Overlays

### Canvas

Overlays must match the OBS Base (Canvas) Resolution exactly. For OIS, this is **1920 × 1080px**. If streaming at 1440p in the future, overlays would need to be 2560 × 1440px.

### Format

**PNG-32 (RGBA)** — 8 bits per channel across Red, Green, Blue, and Alpha. In Photoshop, this is "PNG-24" with "Transparency" checked. PNG-8 only supports binary (on/off) transparency with jagged edges — unsuitable for anti-aliased curves or semi-transparent panels. JPEG cannot carry transparency.

### Color Profile

**sRGB IEC61966-2.1.** OBS performs no color management or ICC profile conversion. Exporting in Adobe RGB or Display P3 will produce desaturated, color-shifted results on stream.

### Performance

Static PNG overlays have negligible performance impact. A typical 1920 × 1080 PNG-32 runs 500 KB to 5 MB and composites trivially on the GPU once loaded. The real performance concerns are animated overlays (video decode), browser sources running JavaScript, and excessive scene nesting (each nested scene adds ~4–8% GPU load).

Separate overlay elements into individual PNG files for independent toggling via Stream Deck.

---

## DPI by Viewing Distance

The human eye stops resolving additional detail at a distance determined by the formula: **DPI = 3,438 ÷ viewing distance in inches.** This means large products viewed from far away need far fewer pixels than small products held up close.

| Product | Typical distance | Required DPI | Practical minimum pixels |
|---|---|---|---|
| Coaster | 12–18″ (hand) | 250–300 | 1,122 × 1,122 |
| Classic Mouse Pad | 18–24″ (desk) | 200–300 | 2,610 × 2,130 |
| Gaming Mouse Pad | 18–24″ (desk) | 200–300 | 5,400 × 4,800 |
| Desk Mat | 24–30″ (arm) | 150–250 | 3,100 × 6,300 (200 DPI) |
| 10×10 Poster | 2–3 ft (wall) | 150–200 | 2,000 × 2,000 |
| 18×24 Poster | 3–5 ft (wall) | 100–150 | 3,600 × 4,800 (200 DPI) |
| 24×36 Poster | 4–6 ft (wall) | 75–120 | 4,800 × 7,200 (200 DPI) |

**Always upload the highest resolution available.** Fourthwall handles downsampling. These minimums are for evaluating whether a source file is usable — not export targets.

---

## AI Upscaling — When It Works and When It Doesn't

AI upscaling at **2× to 4× magnification** from a clean source produces reliable print-quality results. Beyond 4×, quality degrades rapidly — outputs develop a waxy, plastic appearance as the algorithm invents detail that doesn't exist in the source.

### When to use it

- Source is clean, sharp, and artifact-free
- Target magnification is 2–4×
- Product is viewed at arm's length or farther (desk mats, posters)
- Source was high quality to begin with

### When not to use it

- Source is heavily compressed, noisy, or blurry
- Target magnification exceeds 4×
- Product is handheld (coasters, phone cases)
- Text is present (AI garbles letterforms at high magnification)
- Source is pixel art (AI "smooths" intentional pixel edges)

### Artifacts to inspect at 100% zoom

- **Plastic/waxy texture** replacing natural detail
- **Haloing** — bright outlines around high-contrast edges
- **Text corruption** — garbled or misshapen letters
- **Gradient banding** — smooth gradients breaking into steps
- **Texture hallucination** — AI inventing repeating patterns

### QA workflow

1. Clean and denoise the source first
2. Upscale
3. Apply light sharpening last
4. Never sharpen before upscaling — AI magnifies sharpening halos
5. Inspect at 100% zoom before committing to production

